<span id="freeTextContainer5428845125225636500">I&apos;d given it 10 stars if it were possible! I&apos;d read it before, and it was my second time, but still it was new and full of surprises and wit. William Faulkner had put it justly to have called him &quot;the father of American literature&quot;. <br/>The adventures of Tom Sawyer was just witty and adventurous, however, those of Hucklebbery Finn were just more mature. The character of Huck developed as well most beautifully and even in his way of narrating the story and his writing it was apparent! <br/>I especially ad</span>
  <span id="freeText5428845125225636500" style="display:none">I'd given it 10 stars if it were possible! I'd read it before, and it was my second time, but still it was new and full of surprises and wit. William Faulkner had put it justly to have called him "the father of American literature". <br />The adventures of Tom Sawyer was just witty and adventurous, however, those of Hucklebbery Finn were just more mature. The character of Huck developed as well most beautifully and even in his way of narrating the story and his writing it was apparent! <br />I especially admire the part that Huck was talking about languages (French and English to be specific) to Jim and how Jim analyzed the difference between languages most subversively! The next witty passage that has stuck to my mind, is where Huck is talking about 'kings' in general and comparing them to those charlatans. It was amazing! <br />Yes, definitely I'm going to read it again. <br />All thanks to Mr. Samuel Langhorne Clemens and of course Mrs. Clemens for editing the books! :)</span>
